My quality score plotting script:

#!/usr/bin/env python


###qscore script to generate per base call distribution of quality scores for illumina fastq files. 
###script also averages the Quality scores for each read.


import argparse

# Usage:
    # ps5script.py -f seq.fq
    # ps5script.py --file seq.fq


def get_arguments():
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description="generate per base call distribution of quality scores")
    parser.add_argument("-i", "--infile", help="fastq file", required=True, type=str)
    return parser.parse_args()
     
args = get_arguments()

print(args.infile) 
infile = args.infile

##import numpy as np


qscorearray = [0]*101 
qlinearray = []

def convert_phred(letter):
    '''converts letter to phred score'''
    #ord() returns an integer representing the Unicode code point of the letter
    q = ord(letter)      
    q = q - 33
    return q

with open(infile, 'r') as fh:
#with open("/home/konwuzu/indx/r2test", 'r') as fh:
    ##initialization for line read increments
    ##LN = line number
    LN = 0  
    #read each line in file                
    for line in fh:         
        line = line.strip()
        
        #line read starts at 0 (linenum =0 inside loop), so qscore line will be a multiple of 3
        if LN % 4 == 3:                
                            
            bp = 0
            
            sumqline = 0
            #read each char in this line
            for char in line:
                q = convert_phred(char)
                 
                sumqline += q
                #updating of mean_score array
                qscorearray[bp] = qscorearray[bp] + q   
                bp += 1                           
            
            #now mean of sum of q line
            sumqline = sumqline//len(line)
            qlinearray.append(sumqline)
                            
        LN += 1 

        if LN % 1000000 == 0:
            print("Now on line", LN)

#updating from sum to mean         
k = 0
while k<101:
    qscorearray[k]=qscorearray[k]/(LN/4)     
    k+=1
             

#print(qlinearray)
#print(qscorearray)

#mean of each position file
with open("mean_q_bp_"+infile, "w") as out1:
    out1.write("Base pair" + "\t" + "Mean" + "\n")
    a = 0
    #initializing w 1 for base position, a =0 bc of python 0 indexing
    c = 1
    for val in qscorearray:
        out1.write(str(c)+ "\t" + str(qscorearray[a]) + "\n")
        a += 1 
        c += 1  
    
#mean of each read file 
with open("mean_q_line_"+infile, "w") as out2:
    out2.write("Mean of qline" + "\n")
    b = 0
    for val in qlinearray:
        out2.write(str(qlinearray[b]) + "\n")
        b += 1

Part 2 – Adaptor trimming comparison

Look into the adaptor trimming options for cutadapt, process_shortreads, and Trimmomatic (all on Talapas), and briefly describe the differences.

Cutadapt: N-tolerant and written in python. It also processes gzipped files without a flag.

Process_shortreads: can exclude reads with low quality scores or uncalled bases and collects orphaned reads separately. Process_shortreads also requires that you specify gzipped files with a flag.

Trimmomatic (unlike cutadapt and process_shortreads) takes the adapter sequences in a fasta file and not as with a flag. It is also written in Java.

Pick one of these to properly trim adapter sequences. Use default settings.

Process_shortreads srun script:

17_3E_fox

The adapter trimming results are consistent with the insert size distribution of the library. The Fragment Analyzer report shows that the mean insert size of the libraries were ~400bp. Demonstrate convincingly that the SF-Seq data are from “strand-specific” RNA-Seq libraries. There are a number of possible strategies to address this problem, but you need only implement one. Report your evidence in numeric and graphical (e.g. a plot) forms.

In a strand specific library, there would be an abundance of polyA tail in one of the reads. By greping for at least 15 consecutive A or T nucleotides, comparisons of the ration of A to T in the reads can signify the strandedness of my library.

In both files, the unequal ratio of A to T nucleotides signifies that our library was starnd specific.
